e to Britain fleeing political persecution in Germany and Austria. Based on the personal and organisational files that MI5 kept on political refugees during the 1930s and 1940s – which have only recently been released into the public domain – this study also fills a considerable gap in historical research. Telling a story of absorbing interest, which at times reads more like spy fiction, it is both a study of MI5 and of the political refugees themselves. The book will interest academics in the fields of history, politics, intelligence studies, Jewish studies, German studies and migration studies; but it is also accessible to the general reader interested in Britain before, during and after the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAustriansxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aAustrianszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aGermansxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aGermanszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntelligence servicexHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aIntelligence servicezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical refugeesxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aPolitical refugeeszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRefugeesxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRefugeeszGreat Britain. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Intelligence & Espionage.2bisacsh  aEspionage.  aGerman political exiles.  aGerman-speaking refugees.  aInformers.  aIntelligence.  aMI5.  aSecurity Service.  aSurveillance.1 aBrinson, Charmian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDove, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDove, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package: